Business understanding¶

In finance, a loan is the lending of money by one or more individuals, organizations or other entities to other individuals, organizations etc. The recipient (i.e. the borrower) incurs a debt, and is usually liable to pay interest on that debt until it is repaid, and also to repay the principal amount borrowed.

A loan in time enables the borrower to meet financial goals. At the same time, the interest associated with the loan generates revenues for the lender.

However, there is always a risk associated with lending, especially in case of customers having insufficient or non-existent credit histories. If the borrower defaults a loan, then that loan becomes non-performing asset (or, NPA) for the lender. Any NPA hits the bottom-line of the lending organization.

Therefore, every lending organization strives to assess the risk associated with the loan. Primarily, they want to assess their clients' repayment abilities well in advance before deciding on approval and disbursement of loans. Objective of this project is to build a loan default risk classifier. The classifier will be supervised classifier who can be trained on historical data, and classify a new loan accordingly.

Home Credit maintains all historical records related to loan applications. Objective of this project is to build a classifier that, depending on the loan application, can predict whether an applicant will be able to repay the loan or not. This classifier will help bank to approve or reject a loan application efficiently.

Data Understanding¶

In this project, we shall use loan application data provided by Home Credit Group.

This project will build a supervised binary classifier which will predict as follows:

  • Output label as '0': will repay loan on time
  • Output label as '1': will have difficulty in repaying loan or will default

Following data will be used:

  • loan_applications.csv: CSV containing data on loan applications. Each row in this CSV represents one loan.
  • loan_applications_columns_description.csv: This file contains descriptions for the columns of loan applications data

2.1. Handle outliers¶

In [5]:
def handle_outliers(df, col_name, threshold_max, threshold_min = 0, value_to_be_replaced = np.nan):
    '''
    This function handles outliers for a column of the dataframe. 
    Any value that is greater than threshold_max or less than threshold_min is considered as an outlier.
    All such outliers will be replaced with value_to_be_replaced
    INPUT:
    df - Dataframe for which outliers need to be handled
    col_name - column name for which outliers need to be handled
    threshold_max - Any value greater than this will be considered as an outlier
    threshold_min - Any value less than this will be considered as an outlier
    value_to_be_replaced - all outliers will be replaced by this value
    OUTPUT:
    df - dataframe after outliers are handled
    '''
    # any value above or below the threshold will be considered as outlier
    is_outlier = (df[col_name] > threshold_max) | (df[col_name] < threshold_min)
    df_anomalous = df[is_outlier]
    num_of_outlier_rows = len(df_anomalous.index)
    
    if num_of_outlier_rows > 0:
        # print all those unique outlier values
        outliers = df_anomalous[col_name].unique()
        print("List of unique outlier values in '{}' column, as found: {}".format(col_name, str(outliers)))
        
        # replace all outliers
        df.loc[is_outlier, col_name] = value_to_be_replaced
        print('Number of rows updated: ', str(num_of_outlier_rows))
    else:
        print("No outlier found for column '{}'.".format(col_name))
    
    del df_anomalous
    gc.collect()
    
    return df
In [6]:
def select_data_by_values(df, col_name, valid_values):
    '''
    This function selects only those rows where value under col_name belongs to valid_values
    INPUT:
    df - Dataframe for which outliers need to be handled
    col_name - column name for which outliers need to be handled
    valid_values - list of valid values supported
    OUTPUT:
    df - dataframe after outliers are handled
    '''
    rows_before = len(df.index)
    df = df[df[col_name].isin(valid_values)]
    rows_after = len(df.index)
    
    # print some good messages
    rows_filtered = rows_before - rows_after
    if rows_filtered > 0:
        print('Number of rows excluded: ', str(rows_filtered))
    else:
        print("No outlier found for column '{}'.".format(col_name))
    
    return df

def plot_missing_data(df):
    '''
    This function accepts a dataframe.
    For this dataframe, the function
    1. computes percentage of missing value for each column, and,
    2. plots the data in a graph.
    INPUT:
    df - dataframe on which missing data % needs to be computed and plotted
    OUTPUT: Plot on missing data
    '''
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(18,6))
    
    # percentage of missing data in the dataframe
    missing = pd.DataFrame((df.isnull().sum())*100/df.shape[0]).reset_index()
    
    ax = sns.pointplot("index", 0, data=missing)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=7)
    plt.title('Percentage of missing values in the data')
    plt.ylabel('PERCENTAGE')
    plt.xlabel('COLUMNS')
    ax.set_facecolor('k')
    fig.set_facecolor('lightgrey')
In [24]:

As we can see, there are columns where more than 60% of data are missing.
There are two ways to handle missing data:

  1. Imputation i.e. filling up those missing values
  2. Dropping columns having most of the values missing


Dropping columns can be risky and may impair building our model. So, as of now, we shall keep all columns.

2.3.1 Strategy for encoding¶

I shall use Label Encoding and One-Hot Encoding for categorical variables.
Advantage of label encoding is that no new column is created. However, this encoding gives the categories arbitrary ordering. The value assigned to each of the categories is random.
On other hand, one-hot encoding creates a new column for each unique category in a categorical variable. So, this encoding increases the dimentionality of the data.
Therefore, my strategy will be as follows:

  • Apply Label Encoding, if number of categories in a categorical variable is equal to 2
  • Apply One-Hot Encoding, if number of categories in a categorical variable is greater than 2


Please note: For a categorical variable, number of unique values (or, categories) is always greater than or equal to 2.

2.3.2 Label encoding¶

def plot_distribution_of_output_labels(data, plot_title, output_col=None):
    '''
    This function plots distribution of output labels in a pie-chart.
    INPUT:
    data: data set
    plot_title: title of the plot
    output_col: the column containing output labels
    OUtPUT: pie-chart on output-labels
    '''
    plt.figure(figsize=(14,7))
    plt.subplot(121)
    if(output_col is None):
        data.value_counts().plot.pie(
            autopct = "%1.2f%%", colors = sns.color_palette("muted"), startangle = 60,
            labels = ["repayer","defaulter"],
            wedgeprops = {"linewidth":2,"edgecolor":"k"}, explode = [.1,0], shadow = True)
    else:
        data[output_col].value_counts().plot.pie(
            autopct = "%1.2f%%", colors = sns.color_palette("muted"), startangle = 60,
            labels = ["repayer","defaulter"],
            wedgeprops = {"linewidth":2,"edgecolor":"k"}, explode = [.1,0], shadow = True)
    plt.title(plot_title)

def kde_plot_with_target(col_name):
    '''
    This function generates kernel density estimation plot (KDE) of input column with the TARGET.
    This function works on 'app_data' dataframe
    INPUT:
    col_name: Name of the input column
    OUTPUT:
    KDE plot with TARGET
    '''
    plt.figure(figsize = (10, 8))

    # KDE plot of loans that were repaid on time
    sns.kdeplot(app_data.loc[app_data['TARGET'] == 0, col_name], label = 'Repaid in time')

    # KDE plot of loans which were not repaid on time
    sns.kdeplot(app_data.loc[app_data['TARGET'] == 1, col_name], label = 'Difficulty in payment')

    # Labeling of plot
    plt.xlabel(col_name) 
    plt.ylabel('Density') 
    plt.title('Distribution of {} by TARGET'.format(col_name))

4.3 Perform Dimensionality Reduction¶

As we have seen, dimension of data is 240, excluding output label. We have already scaled our data as well. Now, we shall attempt to reduce dimensionality of this data-set.
Working with data in high-dimensional space often results in the problem, known as curse of dimensionality. Therefore, dimensionality reduction will help us to avoid that problem.

Overall strategy:

  • Step 1 - Exclude 'TARGET' from app data
  • Step 2 - Reduce dimensionality of data (excluding 'TARGET')
  • Step 3 - Inspect few features
  • Step 4 - Reconstruct the data set

Step 1 - Exclude 'TARGET' from app data¶

We shall keep training labels separate.

Step 2 - Reduce dimensionality of data¶

Use sklearn's PCA class to apply principal component analysis on the data. This will help in finding the vectors of maximal variance in the data.

Strategy:

  • Let's first fit PCA to entire data set
  • Then, create a scree plot explaining variance per principal component
  • From this plot, decide on number of principal components to be retained
  • Then, re-apply PCA with that many n_components and reduce dimensionality of the data set accordingly

In [56]:
def scree_plot(pca):
    '''
    Creates a scree plot associated with the principal components 
    
    INPUT: pca - PCA in scikit learn
            
    OUTPUT:
            None
    '''
    num_components=len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
    ind = np.arange(num_components)
    vals = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
 
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax = plt.subplot(111)
    cumvals = np.cumsum(vals)
    ax.bar(ind, vals)
    ax.plot(ind, cumvals)
    for i in range(num_components):
        ax.annotate(r"%s%%" % ((str(vals[i]*100)[:4])), (ind[i]+0.2, vals[i]), va="bottom", ha="center", fontsize=12)
 
    ax.xaxis.set_tick_params(width=0)
    ax.yaxis.set_tick_params(width=2, length=12)
 
    ax.set_xlabel("Principal Component")
    ax.set_ylabel("Variance Explained (%)")
    plt.title('Explained Variance Per Principal Component')
    
print("Function 'scree_plot' has been defined.")

In [60]:
def pca_weights(pca, i, df_train):
    '''
    Map weights for the ith principal component to corresponding feature names,
    and return the sorted list of weights.
    INPUT:
    pca: the PCA component
    i: location of the component
    df_train: training dataset
    OUTPUT:
    weights: weights associated
    '''
    df = pd.DataFrame(pca.components_, columns=list(df_train.columns))
    weights = df.iloc[i].sort_values(ascending=False)
    return weights
In [61]:
def plot_PCA_feature_associations(pca, i, df_train):
    '''
    Map weights for the ith principal component to corresponding feature names,
    and then plot linked values, sorted by weight.
    INPUT:
    pca: the PCA component
    i: location of the component
    df_train: training dataset
    OUTPUT: none
    '''
    row = pca_weights(pca, i, df_train)
    row.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(18, 8))
    plt.show()

In [65]:
def form_dataframe(data, pc_count, pc_name_prefix):
    '''
    Form dataframe from n-dimensional data.
    Column names will be formed from given prefix and internal counter value
    INPUT:
    data: n-dimensional array of data (output of PCA)
    pc_count: count of principal components
    pc_name_prefix: prefix for the column names
    OUTPUT:
    df: created dataframe
    '''
    df_cols = []
    for i in range(pc_count):
        column_name = pc_name_prefix + '_' + str(i)
        df_cols.append(column_name)
    df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns = df_cols)
    
    return df

Part 5 - Select classification model and metrics¶

In this part, data to be used is contained in 'app_pca_df' dataframe. We shall create training and test data from this set and evaluate multiple models.

5.1 - Prepare training and test data¶

As we have seen in section 3.1, 8.07% data contains 'TARGET' as 1. 91.93% data contains 'TARGET' as 0. So, we want train and test data to have, at least, nearly similar distribution. In this situation, we can check on following two strategies.

Strategy 1¶

  • Segregate data into two groups i.e. data_set_0 and data_set_1, based on 'TARGET' value as 0 and 1 respectively
  • For each data set, separate output labels (i.e. 'TARGET' column) from input parameters
  • Split each of these subsets into training set and test set using 80:20 ratio.
    • This will create following 4 sets from data_set_0: X_train_0, X_test_0, Y_train_0, Y_test_0
    • Simialrly, 4 sets from data_set_1 will be created: X_train_1, X_test_1, Y_train_1, Y_test_1
  • Create training data by merging:
    • input parameters for training: merge X_train_0 and X_train_1
    • output labels for training: merge Y_train_0 and Y_train_1
  • Create test data by merging:
    • input parameters for testing: merge X_test_0 and X_test_1
    • output labels for testing: merge Y_test_0 and Y_test_1

Strategy 2¶

  • Split data into output labels and input features
  • Split labels and features into training and test sets keeping 80:20 ratio

Define function for strategy 1

In [70]:
def split_test_train_strategy1(df, output_col):
    '''
    This function splits data into training and test sets,
    based on the strategy 1 described above.
    INPUT:
    df: dataframe containing data
    output_col: output column containing labels
    OUTPUT:
    X_train: Input parameters for training
    X_test: Input parameters for testing
    Y_train: Output labels for training
    Y_test: Output labels for testing
    '''
    # create X, Y with having label 0
    data_set_0 = df[df[output_col] == 0]
    Y_0 = data_set_0[output_col]
    X_0 = data_set_0.drop([output_col], axis=1)
    # create X, Y having label 1
    data_set_1 = df[df[output_col] == 1]
    Y_1 = data_set_1[output_col]
    X_1 = data_set_1.drop([output_col], axis=1)
    # split into train, test
    X_train_0, X_test_0, Y_train_0, Y_test_0 = train_test_split(X_0, Y_0, test_size=0.2, random_state = 40)
    X_train_1, X_test_1, Y_train_1, Y_test_1 = train_test_split(X_1, Y_1, test_size=0.2, random_state = 40)
    X_train = pd.concat([X_train_0, X_train_1], ignore_index=True)
    Y_train = pd.concat([Y_train_0, Y_train_1], ignore_index=True)
    X_test = pd.concat([X_test_0, X_test_1], ignore_index=True)
    Y_test = pd.concat([Y_test_0, Y_test_1], ignore_index=True)
    
    return X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test

Define function for strategy 2

In [71]:
def split_test_train_strategy2(df, output_col):
    '''
    This function splits data into training and test sets,
    based on the strategy 2 described above.
    INPUT:
    df: dataframe containing data
    output_col: output column containing labels
    OUTPUT:
    X_train: Input parameters for training
    X_test: Input parameters for testing
    Y_train: Output labels for training
    Y_test: Output labels for testing
    '''
    # create X, Y
    Y = df[output_col]
    X = df.drop([output_col], axis=1)
    # split into train, test
    X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.2, random_state = 40)
    
    return X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test

5.2 - Define metrics to evaluate classification model¶

Let's start with confusion matrix for binary classification.

In [78]:
image = np.array(Image.open(r"images/confusion_matrix.png"))
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.imshow(image,interpolation="bilinear")
plt.axis("off")
fig.set_facecolor("lightgrey")
plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
plt.show()

In our context,

  • output = 1 means client will have payment difficulties
  • output = 0 means client will repay in time

Following metrics will be determined for each of our classification models:

  • Accuracy
    • Accuracy, as name suggests, measures the accuracy of the model in predictions
    • Error = (1 - Accuracy)
    • This metric assumes equal costs for both kinds of errors i.e. false postives and false negatives
    • Accuracy may not be good metric if cost of misclassification/error is high
    • Formula: (TP + TN) / (TP + FP + FN + TN)
  • Recall
    • This metric measures sensitivity of the model
    • Recall shows how many of "actually positives" are predicted as "true positives" by the model
    • Recall is a good metric when the cost of 'False Negative' is high. In our context, 'False Negative' means approving loan to a client when there is chance of defaulting.
    • Formula: (True Positives) / (Actually Positives) = TP / (TP + FN)
  • Precision
    • Precision shows how precise the model is in predicting postives.
    • Precision is a good metric when the cost of 'False Positive' is high. In our context, 'False Positive' means loosing a good client.
    • Formula: (True Positives) / (Predicted Positives) = TP / (TP + FP)
  • F1 score
    • This is harmonic mean of precision and recall
    • F1 score ranges from 0 (means, worst) to 1 (means, perfect precision and recall)
    • This is a good metric when we want to give equal importance to both precision and recall
    • Formula: 2 (Precision Recall) / (Precision + Recall)
  • Receiver Operating Characteristic curve and Area Under Curve (ROC curve and AUC)
    • ROC curve is used to assess the performance of the classifier over its entire operating range
    • For a perfect classifier the ROC curve will go straight up the Y axis and then along the X axis
    • Diagonal curve indicates worst power of the classifier
    • Area Under Curve (AUC) is the most common metric related to ROC curve
    • AUC for most classifiers usually ranges between 0.5 (that means, classifier is probably randomly guessing) to 1 (that means, perfect classifier)
    • AUC < 0.5 means something is wrong with the model or the data or both

Let's now, define a function to evaluate a classification model.

In [79]:
def eval_model(model, dtrain_X, dtrain_Y, dtest_X, dtest_Y, cols=None):
    '''
    This function takes an classification model, fits that model to training data,
    predicts on test data and creates evaluation metrics
    INPUT:
    model: the model to be evaluated
    dtrain_X: training data
    dtrain_Y: training labels
    dtest_X: test data
    dtest_Y: test labels
    cols: columns of the data
    OUTPUT:
    evaluation metrics, ROC curve and the area under the curve
    '''
    model.fit(dtrain_X[cols],dtrain_Y)
    predictions = model.predict(dtest_X[cols])
    print(model)
    
    print("Accuracy score: ", accuracy_score(predictions,dtest_Y))
    print("Recall score: ", recall_score(predictions,dtest_Y))
    print("Classification report:\n",classification_report(predictions,dtest_Y))
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    prediction_probabilities = model.predict_proba(dtest_X[cols])[:,1]
    fpr , tpr , thresholds = roc_curve(dtest_Y,prediction_probabilities)
    ax.plot(fpr,tpr,label = ["Area under curve : ",auc(fpr,tpr)],linewidth=2,linestyle="dotted")
    ax.plot([0,1],[0,1],linewidth=2,linestyle="dashed")
    plt.legend(loc="best")
    plt.title("ROC-CURVE and AREA UNDER CURVE")
    ax.set_facecolor("k")

ROC AUC as metric for model selection¶

For our model selection, we shall use each model's ROC AUC value.

ROC AUC¶

Area under ROC curve is a performance measurement for classification problem at various thresholds settings. ROC is a probability curve and AUC represents degree or measure of separability. It tells how much model is capable of distinguishing between classes.

In [80]:
image = np.array(Image.open(r"images/ROC_AUC.png"))
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.imshow(image,interpolation="bilinear")
plt.axis("off")
fig.set_facecolor("lightgrey")
plt.title("ROC curve and AUC")
plt.show()

Please refer to the confusion matrix above, in section 5.2 to understand certain terms used below.

TPR or true positive rate is a measure for 'recall' or sensitivity. FPR or false positive rate is a measure for expectancy of the false positives from the model.

TPR = TP / (TP + FN)

FPR = 1 - specificity = 1 - TN / (TN + FP) = FP / (TN + FP)

AUC ranges in value from 0 to 1. Higher the AUC, better the model is at predicting who will repay the loan in time and who will have difficulties in repaying the loan.

AUC as a metric is appropriate for following reasons:

  • AUC provides an aggregate measure of performance across all possible classification thresholds.
  • AUC is scale-invariant. It measures how well predictions are ranked, rather than their absolute values.
  • AUC is classification-threshold-invariant. It measures the quality of the model's predictions irrespective of what classification threshold is chosen.

6.3 Cross validation and early stopping¶

Each combination of hyperparameter values needs to be evaluated. The evaluation cannot be done using test data. The model should see test data only once. Therefore, a portion of training data needs to keep aside for validation. This set is called 'validation set'. However, if we use KFold cross validation, then we don't need to keep separate validation set. The performance of each set of hyperparameters is determined by Receiver Operating Characteristic Area Under the Curve (ROC AUC) from the cross-validation.

In machine learning, early stopping is a form of regularization used to avoid overfitting when training a learner. Here, early stopping means training until the validation error does not decrease for a specified number of iterations.

We shall use 5-fold validation.

In [94]:

6.5 Hyperparameter Tuning¶

We need to define following four aspects of this hyperparameter tuning:

  • Objective function: a function that takes in hyperparameters and returns a score. Objective is either to minimize or maximize this score
  • Domain: the set of hyperparameters whose optimum values we want to search
  • Algorithm: method for selecting the next set of hyperparameters to evaluate in the objective function
  • Results history: data structure containing each set of hyperparameters and corresponding score from the objective function

6.5.1 Objective function¶

Let's first define the objective function. This objective function will be used in grid search and will return cross-validation ROC AUC score from the set of hyperparameters.

  • Score to be used: ROC AUC
  • Objective: maximize this ROC AUC score
In [100]:
def objective(hyperparameters, iteration):
    '''
    Objective function for grid search. 
    Returns the cross validation score from a set of hyperparameters.
    INPUT:
    hyperparameters: hyperparameters of the model
    iteration: number of the iteration
    OUTPUT:
    Array of ROC AUC score, hyperparameters and iteration number
    '''
    
    # Number of estimators will be found using early stopping
    if 'n_estimators' in hyperparameters.keys():
        del hyperparameters['n_estimators']
    
    # Perform n_folds cross validation
    cv_results = lgb.cv(hyperparameters, train_set, num_boost_round = 10000, nfold = N_FOLDS, 
                        early_stopping_rounds = 100, metrics = 'auc', seed = 42)
    
    # results to retun
    score = cv_results['auc-mean'][-1]
    hyperparameters['n_estimators'] = len(cv_results['auc-mean']) 
    
    return [score, hyperparameters, iteration]

6.5.3 Algorithm¶

The process of choosing the set of hyperparameter depends on the algorithm. In this notebook, following two algorithms will be used:

  • Grid search: The 'domain' contains the hyperparameter-grid. The grid search method tries all combinations of values in the grid, evaluates each combination of hyperparameter with the objective function and records the set along with the score in the 'record history'. The 'record history' is sorted according to the score.
    • Limitations:
      • Grid search is extremely computationally expensive because we have to perform cross validation with every single combination of hyperparameters in the grid.
      • Result depends on the choice of the grid. The algorithm only chooses best combination of values from the set of available values in the hyperparameter-grid.
  • Random search: This algorithm differs from grid-search only in the method of choosing the combination of hyperparameters. As the name suggests, this algorithm randomly selects the next set of hyperparameters from the grid. This is uninformed search which means next selection of hyperparameters does not rely on past evaluation results. Once a set of hyperparameters is chosen, then just like grid search, that combination of hyperparameters is evaluated with the objective function and evaluation is recorded in the 'record history'. The 'record history' is sorted according to the score.

6.5.3.1 Grid search¶

Let's implement grid search algorithm. In the case of grid search, we input the domain and the algorithm selects the next value for each hyperparameter in an ordered sequence. The only requirement of grid search is that it tries every combination in a grid once (and only once).

Usually, in grid search, we do not limit the number of evaluations. The number of evaluations is set by the total combinations in the hyperparameter grid. However, let's see the number of combinations we have.

In [104]:
com = 1
for x in param_grid.values():
    com *= len(x)
print('There are {} combinations in the hyperparameter grid.'.format(com))

There are 546000000000000000 combinations in the hyperparameter grid.

Evidently, if we don't 'hard-stop' our grid search with something like maximum number of evaluations, this grid search will take years to test each combination with cross-validation.

In [105]:
def grid_search(param_grid, max_evals = MAX_EVALS):
    '''
    Grid search algorithm (with limit on max evals)
    INPUT:
    param_grid: The grid of hyperparameters
    max_evals: maximum number of evaluations
    OUTPUT:
    results: results history
    '''
    
    # Dataframe to store results
    results = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['score', 'params', 'iteration'],
                              index = list(range(max_evals)))
    
    keys, values = zip(*param_grid.items())
    
    i = 0
    
    # Iterate through every possible combination of hyperparameters
    for v in itertools.product(*values):
        
        # Create a hyperparameter dictionary
        hyperparameters = dict(zip(keys, v))
        
        # Set the subsample ratio accounting for boosting type
        hyperparameters['subsample'] = 1.0 if hyperparameters['boosting_type'] == 'goss' else hyperparameters['subsample']
        
        # Evalute the hyperparameters
        eval_results = objective(hyperparameters, i)
        
        results.loc[i, :] = eval_results
        
        i += 1
        
        # Normally would not limit iterations
        if (i >= max_evals):
            break
       
    # Sort with best score on top
    results.sort_values('score', ascending = False, inplace = True)
    results.reset_index(inplace = True)
    
    return results

6.5.3.2 Random search¶

Let's implement random search algorithm. Random search is always run with a limit on the number of search iterations.

In [106]:
def random_search(param_grid, max_evals = MAX_EVALS):
    '''
    Random search for hyperparameter optimization (with limit on max evals)
    INPUT:
    param_grid: The grid of hyperparameters
    max_evals: maximum number of evaluations
    OUTPUT:
    results: results history
    '''
    
    # Dataframe for results
    results = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['score', 'params', 'iteration'],
                                  index = list(range(MAX_EVALS)))
    
    # Keep searching until reach max evaluations
    for i in range(max_evals):
        
        # Choose random hyperparameters
        hyperparameters = {k: random.sample(v, 1)[0] for k, v in param_grid.items()}
        hyperparameters['subsample'] = 1.0 if hyperparameters['boosting_type'] == 'goss' else hyperparameters['subsample']

        # Evaluate randomly selected hyperparameters
        eval_results = objective(hyperparameters, i)
        
        results.loc[i, :] = eval_results
    
    # Sort with best score on top
    results.sort_values('score', ascending = False, inplace = True)
    results.reset_index(inplace = True)
    
    return results

6.5.4 Results history¶

The results history is a data structure that contains the collection (that means, history) of results. Each result has following columns: 'score', 'params', 'iteration'. Both grid search and random search will sort result history according to the score, in descending order.

Testing the model over multiple sets of data¶

In this section, we shall split data into multiple sets. For each set, we shall compute ROC AUC score of the model. Then, we shall see those scores to assess robustness of the model.

Let us first define a function that can test the model over multiple folds of data. This function we shall reuse later during optimization using random search algorithm.

In [135]:
def kfold_lightgbm(train_df, train_target, clf, num_folds=5):
    '''
    This function splits data into multiple folds,
    compute ROC AUC score of the model for each set, and,
    print and return the scores.
    INPUT:
    train_df: input features of training data
    train_target: output labels of training data 
    clf: the model to be tested
    num_folds: number of sets the data should be split into. Default is 5.
    OUTPUT:
    scores: the dataframe containing scores
    '''
    print("Starting LightGBM. Input data shape: {}".format(train_df.shape))
    # Cross validation model
    folds = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=47)
    # Create arrays and dataframes to store results
    oof_preds = np.zeros(train_df.shape[0])
    scores = pd.DataFrame(columns=['n_fold', 'Score'])
    
    for n_fold, (train_idx, valid_idx) in enumerate(folds.split(train_df, train_target)):
        train_x, train_y = train_df.iloc[train_idx], train_target.iloc[train_idx]
        valid_x, valid_y = train_df.iloc[valid_idx], train_target.iloc[valid_idx]

        clf.fit(train_x, train_y, eval_set=[(train_x, train_y), (valid_x, valid_y)], 
            eval_metric='auc', verbose=1000, early_stopping_rounds=300)

        oof_preds[valid_idx] = clf.predict_proba(valid_x, num_iteration=clf.best_iteration_)[:, 1]
        score = roc_auc_score(valid_y, oof_preds[valid_idx])
        n_fold_num = n_fold + 1
        #print('Fold %2d AUC : %.6f' % (n_fold_num, score))
        #scores.append(score)
        scores = scores.append({'n_fold': n_fold_num, 'Score': score}, ignore_index=True)
        del train_x, train_y, valid_x, valid_y
        gc.collect()

    return scores

6.6 Conclusion on model optimization¶

  • In this notebook, two strategies were demonstrated, which are grid search and random search, to select best combination of hyperparameters for LGBMClassifier.
  • In order to limit consumption of hardware resources:
    • only a small subset of training and test data have been used to demonstrate model tuning. This has been explained in sections 6.1 and 6.2. In reality, entire training and test data can be used.
    • Grid search and random search have been evaluated only 5 times. In reality, higher number of iterations can be tried.
    • Only a small subset of hyperparameters and a limited number of their values have been chosen to create hyperparameter-grid, in section 6.5.2. In reality, we can include more hyperparameters and more values. However, computational complexity polynomially increases with the increase in dimension of hyperparameter-grid.
  • We have observed only marginal improvement in ROC AUC metric, after hyperparameter tuning. This is mainly attributed to following reasons:
    • Small set of data chosen
    • small set of hyperparameters chosen
    • Small number of iterations in grid search and random search
  • We have tested the model on different sets of data. We have found that the model is quite stable.
  • I haven't used GridSearchCV or RandomizedSearchCV for following reasons:
    • In our objective function, I have used KFold cross validation, as implemented by LightGBM cross validation function, cv. Here, I could use early stopping which is critical for training a GBM.
    • Both of GridSearchCV and RandomizedSearchCV are computationally intensive. Their parallel processing and in-memory operations require high CPU and RAM.

Summary and Reflection¶

In this notebook, we have studied various factors related to a financial loan, which governs the risk associated with the repayment in time.

We have analyzed the data, rectified few anomalies, imputed missing values, encoded categorical features and finally reduced the dimension of the data using PCA. We also have observed 'class imbalance problem' related to the data.

We have evaluated several classification models and have chosen light GBM classifier for classifying the defaulting risk. We have also chosen ROC AUC metric for measuring the performance of the models. Chosen model has scored around 0.7 which is not that bad. Mostly, it was the data which need to be more balanced across output labels.

Now, let's see what is AUC score 0.7 means.

In [153]:
image = np.array(Image.open(r"images/AUC_interpretation.png"))
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.imshow(image,interpolation="bilinear")
plt.axis("off")
fig.set_facecolor("lightgrey")
plt.title("Distribution of positive and negative curves")
plt.show()

Red distribution curve is of the positive class (borrower may default) and green distribution curve is of negative class (borrower will repay in time).

As we know, AUC represents degree or measure of separability. Higher the AUC, better the model is at predicting 0s as 0s and 1s as 1s.

When two distributions overlap, type 1 and type 2 errors are introduced. Depending upon the threshold, we can minimize or maximize them. When AUC is 0.7, it means there is 70% chance that model will be able to distinguish between positive class and negative class.

This means, our model will be correct on 70% times in identifying a borrower having risk of defaulting a loan.

Finally, we have demonstrated how chosen model can be tuned to optimize its performance. Though, we have some limitations in resources, but tuning processes as shown, can be followed to optimize LGBMClassifier in real-world scenario.

Key learnings¶

  • Finding right data is key to success of any datascience problem.
  • Finding right model is next important aspect.
  • Companies investing on datascience should spend on proper infrastructure, data governance and data strategies

Improvement¶

In this section, let us discuss few aspects of the implementation that can be improved.

Improvement 1 - imputing missing values¶

In case of imputing missing values in section 4.1, NaN were filled with 'median' values. 'Median' works well when the data is sorted. A better approach will certainly be using a supervised learning model to 'predict' the NaN values.

However, imputation of data means introduction of data by data analysis. This will always add some bias, however negligible its effect is. Certain model like XGBoost can handle NaN in data.

Improvement 2 - selection of hyperparameters for LGBMClassifier¶

In section 6.5.2 we have selected a subset of hyperparameters. In sections 6.5.3 and 6.5.4, we have performed grid search and random search to select best set values on the hyperparameters.

Smarter technique can be combining random search and grid search as follows:

  • Use random search with large hyperparameter grid
  • Use the results of random search to build a focused hyperparameter grid around the best performing hyperparameter values
  • Run grid search on this reduced hyperparameter grid. We can limit number of iterations or not, depending on hardware resources available or maximum time allowed.
